period cramps

If you suffer from intense period cramps, some kinds of birth control can really help you out. You’ll want to use a hormonal birth control like the pill, ring, shot, patch, implant, or the hormonal IUD. These are known to help reduce cramps and help your period get on track.

The patch is a type of birth control that you place on your arm every week. It’s sold as Xulane (used to be called Ortho Evra) and it works to prevent ovulation (when your body releases an egg) - no egg, no baby!
pills

The pill is a type of birth control that you take once a day, every day, at the same time. Most of them work to prevent ovulation (when your body releases an egg) - no egg, no baby! There are a ton of different kinds of birth control pills out there so if one doesn’t work for you, you have options.

Most people don’t realize it but, there are SO many different types of birth control pills out there. There’s Ortho Tri-Cyclen, Yaz, TriNessa, Yasmin and a bunch of others. What’s the difference? Well, some pills have two hormones to prevent pregnancy (estrogen and progestin) and others just have one but other than that, they’re pretty similar. If you’re thinking about the pill, talk to a doctor so you can figure out the best one for you.
